king reader with a fuller understanding of the uniqueness and quality of the culture of Catalonia by providing a comprehensive portfolio of the creative contribution of the nation across a broad spectrum of achievement. Though the artistic wealth of the medieval period is acknowledged appropriately, this study, with its focus on the modern age, privileges excellence not only in the more conventional, academic spheres of history, music, language, literature and the arts but also explores the value of more basic, popular experience inareas such as sport, cinema, festivals, cuisine and the city of Barcelona. DOMINIC KEOWN is Reader in Catalan at the University of Cambridge. CONTRIBUTORS: Elisenda Barbé, Robert Davidson, Alexander Ibarz, Louise Johnson, Dominic Keown, Tess Knighton, Jaume Martí-Olivella, Dorothy Noyes, Montserrat Roser i Puig, Antoni Segura, Miquel Strubell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCatalansxEthnic identity. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aArts.  aBarcelona.  aBigas Luna.  aCatalan Identity.  aCinema.  aCuisine.  aCulture of Catalonia.  aDalí.  aFestivals.  aGaudí.  aHistory.  aLanguage.  aLiterature.  aMiró.  aMusic.  aSport.1 aBarbe, Elisenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbarz, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeown, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeown, Dominic, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnighton, Tess, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarti-Olivella, Jaume,